            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Page Authority is a Moz proprietary metric, not a Google ranking factor. Google does not use PA in its algorithm. However, PA correlates with actual rankings because it measures backlink quality and quantity — signals that Google does use.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is a good Page Authority score?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Page Authority is relative, not absolute. A good score depends on your competition. As a general guide: 0-20 is new or unlinked pages, 20-40 is average, 40-60 is strong, 60-80 is very strong, 80-100 is exceptional. The practical rule: your target page's PA should equal or exceed the average PA of pages ranking in the top 10 for your keyword.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How can I increase a page's Page Authority?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Page Authority increases primarily through earning high-quality backlinks from authoritative domains. You can also boost it by building internal links from high-PA pages on your own site, improving content quality and depth, fixing technical issues affecting crawlability, and actively promoting content to earn earned links.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
